06312nam a22013215i 9781400840069DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008400697 a10.1515/97814008400692doi  a(DE-B1597)446712  a(OCoLC)979910928  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS57b.M434 2017 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a939.400722231 aMcCants, William F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFounding Gods, Inventing Nations :bConquest and Culture Myths from Antiquity to Islam /cWilliam F. McCants.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Gifts of the Gods: The Origins of Civilization in Ancient Near Eastern and Greek Mythology -- tTwo. The Beneficent Sky God: Cultural History in the Qur'an -- tThree. Who Was First? Protography and Discovery Catalogs -- tFour. Inventing Nations: Postconquest Native Histories of Civilization's Origins -- tFive. "The Sciences of the Ancients": Speculation on the Origins of Philosophy, Medicine, and the Exact Sciences -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the dawn of writing in Sumer to the sunset of the Islamic empire, Founding Gods, Inventing Nations traces four thousand years of speculation on the origins of civilization. Investigating a vast range of primary sources, some of which are translated here for the first time, and focusing on the dynamic influence of the Greek, Roman, and Arab conquests of the Near East, William McCants looks at the ways the conquerors and those they conquered reshaped their myths of civilization's origins in response to the social and political consequences of empire. The Greek and Roman conquests brought with them a learned culture that competed with that of native elites. The conquering Arabs, in contrast, had no learned culture, which led to three hundred years of Muslim competition over the cultural orientation of Islam, a contest reflected in the culture myths of that time. What we know today as Islamic culture is the product of this contest, whose protagonists drew heavily on the lore of non-Arab and pagan antiquity. McCants argues that authors in all three periods did not write about civilization's origins solely out of pure antiquarian interest--they also sought to address the social and political tensions of the day. The strategies they employed and the postcolonial dilemmas they confronted provide invaluable context for understanding how authors today use myth and history to locate themselves in the confusing aftermath of empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAcculturationvMiddle EastxHistory. 0aAcculturationzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aArabsvMiddle EastxHistory. 0aArabszMiddle EastxHistory. 0aCivilizationvPhilosophy. 0aCivilizationxPhilosophy. 0aGreeksvMiddle EastxHistory. 0aGreekszMiddle EastxHistory. 0aHISTORYvAncientvGeneral. 0aHISTORYvMiddle EastvGeneral. 0aMiddle EastvCivilizationvHistoriography. 0aMiddle EastvCivilizationvPhilosophy. 0aMiddle EastvColonization. 0aMiddle EastvIntellectual life. 0aMythology, Middle Eastern. 0aRomansvMiddle EastxHistory. 0aRomanszMiddle EastxHistory. 0aRomanszMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aArab conquests.  aArabs.  aGreek conquests.  aGreek ethnography.  aGreek philosophy.  aGreeks.  aIbn Qutayba.  aIslam.  aIslamic culture.  aIslamic thinking.  aJews.  aMuhammad.  aNear East.  aPliny.  aQur'an.  aRoman conquests.  aRomans.  aanc